      "content": "thanks, this is a good start for the setting. but to be honest, it feels a bit too \"sanitized\" or like a TV show for kids. in the 50s, these men wouldn't just talk about \"stability\" in such vague, polite terms; their worldview was much more deeply rooted in the idea that certain people simply didn't belong in certain spaces or roles. \n\ncan you go a level deeper with the subtext? for example, instead of just saying \"outsiders,\" maybe they talk about the \"threat\" to their specific social order or how \"they\" are disrupting the way things have always been handled locally. i need the dialogue to capture that specific, condescending sense of entitlement and the assumption that they have a right to control who does what in their town. it doesn't have to be a list of slurs, but it should feel much more grounded in the actual racial hierarchies of the era.",
